Be careful about using plastic tea bags to make tea!
According to the &quot;Central News Agency&quot; report, a recent Canadian study found that a bag of plastic tea bags may release billions or even tens of billions of plastic particles, which is significantly higher than the estimated amount of microplastics a person ingests throughout the year. But so far there is no evidence that ingesting plastic particles poses a threat to humans.
According to reports, researchers from Magill University in Canada found that when a plastic tea bag is immersed in a cup of almost boiling hot water (95 degrees Celsius), the tea bag will release about 11.6 billion plastic particles and 3.1 billion smaller nanoplastic particles. in the cup.
This amount is significantly higher than the amount of microplastics a person is estimated to ingest in an entire year.
According to research published earlier in 2019, the average person eats at least 50,000 plastic particles every year and inhales the same amount of microplastics.
It is reported that this study was published in the &quot;Journal of Environmental Science and Technology&quot;. The researchers tested 4 different types of plastic commercial tea bags in stores and cafes in Montreal. They opened the tea bags, washed the tea bags and immersed them in almost boiling water for 5 minutes. , and then analyzed using an electron microscope and spectrometer.
According to the study, they found that a single tea bag released more than 11.6 billion plastic particles, &quot;several levels higher than previous plastic loads from other foods.&quot;
According to reports, most tea bags are made of natural fibers, but many tea bag brands that use natural fibers still use plastic to seal them.
Some brands of tea bags no longer use paper and instead use plastic, and these plastic tea bags were the subjects of the researchers&#39; tests.
Microplastics are tiny fragments of plastic. Researchers define the size of these microplastics as ranging from 100 nanometers to 5 millimeters. They are mainly produced by the decomposition of plastic waste.
Researchers have found traces of plastic particles in the air, soil, rivers and deepest ocean trenches around the world, and they can also be found in tap water, bottled water, seafood and beer.
In October 2018, researchers first discovered plastic particles in human fecal samples from several countries in different regions of the world.
To test the potential toxicity of plastic particles released from tea bags, the Canadian research team put water fleas into contaminated water and found that microplastics affected the behavior of these water fleas and caused them to develop developmental abnormalities.
According to the World Health Organization (WHO), there is no evidence so far that ingesting plastic particles poses a threat to humans.
However, the WHO noted that more research is needed to fully understand how these plastics spread into the environment and what impact they have on humans.
Researchers speculate that the reason why these tea bags release a large amount of plastic particles may be that these plastic tea bags come into contact with boiling water. Even &quot;food grade&quot; plastic may decompose or leak toxic substances when heated to above 40 degrees Celsius.
Guterres said the climate emergency is the biggest threat to the survival of small island nations.
There, a natural disaster can erode a generation&#39;s worth of development gains.
The disasters in Barbuda, the Dominican Republic and the Bahamas, which have been hit by hurricanes this year, illustrate this point.
About a quarter of the people in small island developing states live at an altitude of 5 meters or less.
Relocation may seriously affect their society and way of life, and even raise issues of sovereignty and national identity.
Small island nations are once again leading the world in the right direction when they join forces at Monday&#39;s Climate Action Summit to commit to becoming carbon neutral and 100% renewable by 2030.
Guterres said: “The climate crisis is piling new injustices on top of old ones.
Although small island developing countries contribute only a small amount to global warming, they pay the highest price.
Due to their middle-income status, many countries are also trapped in an accelerating and unsustainable cycle of disaster and debt.
The world must act. Now is the time to make big decisions and invest heavily in small island developing states. &quot;
Today&#39;s high-level meeting adopted a political declaration calling for ways to help small island developing States manage disaster risks, invest in climate-resilient infrastructure and transition to renewable energy; urging international agencies to help small island developing States Countries, especially heavily indebted middle-income countries, receive funding.
Small island developing States are at the forefront of protecting and conserving the oceans, the lifeline of the planet.
The latest special report from the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, released this week, confirms that oceans are already suffering &quot;sweeping&quot; severe consequences of the climate crisis.
By mid-century, many regions may experience annual levels of extreme sea level rise that would otherwise only occur once a century.
The report warns that without significant investment in adaptation, some island nations are likely to become uninhabitable.
Pollution, overfishing and acidification have taken a huge toll.
In the past 150 years, the world has lost half of all living corals, while plastic pollution has increased tenfold in the past 40 years.
The demands of industry, shipping, mining and tourism are reducing resources, including the fisheries that sustain many island communities.
Small island states also face high costs of transport, energy and infrastructure.
They rely heavily on some external market, making them subject to price fluctuations.
Some countries are also grappling with the security implications of illicit trafficking in people, weapons and drugs.
&quot;By solving a problem in the most challenging environments, it can be solved anywhere,&quot; Guterres said.
The efforts of small island developing States to achieve the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development will provide us with tools, lessons and examples that the world can learn from. &quot;
He emphasized that small island developing countries are special cases of sustainable development.
They require long-term attention and investment from the entire international community.
