“It is estimated that overage migrant workers account for more than half of the workers on some construction sites.
Where to find young workers now?
We don&#39;t want to use so many &#39;old people&#39; on the construction site, there is no other way. &quot;
Recently, Zou Kui, who has been working as an engineering contractor in the construction industry for many years, lamented the fact that there are many overage migrant workers (over the retirement age) on construction sites.
Recently, the university where the author works has carried out a rainwater and sewage diversion project, and many migrant workers have appeared on campus. If you pay attention, you will find that there are many overage migrant workers here.
Overage migrant workers go out to work not because they “can’t have time”, but because they “can’t have time” and have the helplessness and hardship of “having to do this” – whether they are saving money to solve their own pension and medical problems, or to support their children. It drives these old people who should have been &quot;free&quot; to continue to work hard.
It is not as easy as we think for over-age migrant workers to have a place of support in old age.
Raising children, supporting the elderly, providing education for children, helping children build buildings and buy cars, helping children start a family and start a business, and raising grandchildren across generations, when these migrant workers have completed their &quot;life tasks&quot;, their pockets have been emptied and they even have a lot of debt. , most of them lack wealth accumulation.
In order not to hinder their children and to accumulate more wealth for themselves, many migrant workers insist on &quot;working until they can&#39;t work anymore.&quot;
Many new generation migrant workers born in the 1980s, 1990s and even 00s are unwilling to engage in the secondary industry or low-end service industry with difficult conditions and high labor intensity, resulting in a structural &quot;labor shortage&quot;. These lack of Attractive jobs provide opportunities for over-age migrant workers.
Due to lack of skills and reduced physical function and labor ability, many over-age migrant workers are doing jobs that are intensive, low-income, high-risk, and have little security.
The more work you can do, the more you can earn. The survival plight of over-age migrant workers behind the &quot;no idleness&quot; cannot be ignored or ignored.
Solving the problems of wage arrears and wage demands, improving labor protection, reducing safety risks, increasing labor income, and improving the living conditions of overage migrant workers, in addition to their &quot;self-salvation&quot;, are also inseparable from the institutional protection and humanistic care of the public sector.
Some scholars point out that over-age migrant workers are no longer able to rely on returning home to farm to solve their own pension and medical problems. They must find other ways to support their families.
Understanding the helplessness and strength of over-age migrant workers who “cannot be idle” will help us better understand the love and pain of over-age migrant workers.
Seeing the backs of over-age migrant workers, hearing their sighs, and finding ways to make them truly &quot;have someone to support themselves in old age&quot; when they return to the countryside requires the public sector, market and society to share responsibilities in a positive interaction, and requires the joint efforts of many parties.
