E-cigarettes have killed 12 people in the United States, reaching 805 cases of lung damage.
According to the &quot;Central News Agency&quot; report, on the 26th local time, U.S. health officials stated that 12 people have died from e-cigarette-related diseases in the United States, and there were 805 cases of lung damage related to e-cigarette smoking.
The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported the numbers and said the specific substance causing the illnesses has not yet been identified.
However, most patients report using e-cigarette products containing THC, the main psychoactive compound in marijuana.
It is reported that the surge in lung cases is related to the purchase of contaminated e-cigarette atomizers on the black market.
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention pointed out that the 12 deaths occurred in 10 states from California to Florida, while the 805 related confirmed and suspected cases were reported by 46 states and the U.S. Virgin Islands.
In the past three weeks, India and Massachusetts have banned the sale of e-cigarettes, while New York and Michigan have banned flavored e-cigarettes.
According to reports, the Trump administration plans to ban all flavored e-cigarette products except tobacco flavor starting in October.
When does the next bus come?
