It is reported that the exhibition is divided into four exhibition areas: auspicious jade and gold, blessing books and longevity ultimatums, strange craftsmanship and unique arts, and color and splendor. It displays jade and bronze, ancient books and paintings, miscellaneous items, porcelain and enamel and other categories of cultural relics to the audience. The exhibits’ utensils The shape and pattern decoration all reflect the theme of &quot;luck and longevity&quot;.
Wei Lijia, deputy director of the Cultural Relics Department of the Summer Palace Management Office, said that this cultural relics exhibition has a large number of high-level cultural relics, many types of cultural relics, and a wide range of exhibits.
Nearly 30% of the cultural relics on display are national first-class cultural relics and second-class cultural relics, spanning from the Shang Dynasty to the Guangxu period of the Qing Dynasty.
The Zhenggui from the Shang Dynasty on display dates back more than 3,000 years and is the &quot;oldest&quot; bronze cultural relic on display; the sapphire lying cow is huge and weighs nearly 80 kilograms. It is carved from a single piece of sapphire and is preserved They are in good condition and very rare; the wooden clock of the pavilion of mountains, rocks, figures, &quot;Nanzhai Collection Painting Album&quot; and &quot;Nanzhai Collection Calligraphy&quot; are also high-quality cultural relics exhibited to the public for the first time.
Qin Lei, deputy director of the Beijing Summer Palace Management Office, said that this cultural exhibition adheres to the spirit of making cultural relics &quot;alive&quot;, relies on the Summer Palace&#39;s gardening idea of &quot;Fushan, Longevity and Sea&quot;, and uses the cultural relics with the theme of &quot;luck and longevity&quot; in the garden as a carrier to allow tourists to Through the exhibition, you can understand the profound blessing and longevity culture of the Summer Palace, carry forward and inherit Chinese traditional culture, and convey the best wishes for blessing and longevity.
It is reported that the cultural relics exhibition will last until January 30, 2020.
