A Foodworks supermarket boss has been slammed as &quot;disgraceful&quot; after the Fair Work Commission found he fired a 66-year-old female worker via text message because he preferred to hire staff from Asian backgrounds. .
The commission said the way Ms Gail Ayton&#39;s boss, Jianbin Wang, known as Eddie, who has worked at the Wagga Wagga store for more than 20 years, treated staff &quot;grossly unfairly&quot; and may have breached anti-discrimination laws.
Ms Ayton told the committee that Mr Wang, who took over the store in 2016, had been &quot;trying to fire me&quot; because she was not Chinese.
In the case, commission deputy chairman Peter Sams conducted an internet search and found &quot;a number of recruitment advertisements posted by Mr Wang in the past on various Chinese-Australian employment forums&quot;.
Among the job requirements listed for these positions, one said &quot;Asian ladies preferred&quot; and another said &quot;Asian employees preferred.&quot;
A third post said he &quot;prefers overseas people (sic)&quot;.
Mr Wang fired Ms Ayton via text message in April this year, later claiming it was due to her absence from work and a small amount of cash ranging from $5.10 to $30 that was allegedly missing from the cash register.
But Mr Sams said Mr Wang&#39;s reasons for sacking Ms Ayton were weak and lacked evidence.
She had only missed one shift in three years, and the &quot;missing amount&quot; totaled a few dollars.
He said Ms Ayton&#39;s dismissal had &quot;in fact nothing to do with her conduct or performance&quot;.
He said: &quot;In my view, supported by the evidence of the recruitment advertisement posted by Mr Wang, the respondent&#39;s real motive for dismissing her was his preference to employ staff with an Asian background.
Mr Wang&#39;s conduct prima facie constituted a breach of anti-discrimination laws and/or the applicant&#39;s dismissal was unlawful under section 772(f) of the Fair Work Act. &quot;
Mr Sams said given Mr Wang&#39;s &quot;appalling&quot; treatment of Ms Ayton it would be inappropriate for him to consider reinstating her.
He should consider paying compensation to Ms Ayton, who was a casual worker earning $26 an hour.
In light of the potential breaches of anti-discrimination and industrial relations legislation, Sams said he would refer his findings and documents to the commission&#39;s supervisor to consider whether Mr Wang&#39;s conduct should be referred to another agency to investigate possible breaches of state or federal law. the behavior of.
He said Mr Wang did not give Ms Ayton any opportunity to respond to the alleged reasons for her dismissal.
He said: &quot;In my opinion, the respondent adopted a hopelessly unfair and biased procedure to dismiss the applicant, with Mr Wang &#39;waiting&#39; for this opportunity which he believed would &#39;justify&#39; the termination of the applicant&#39;s employment. Legitimate. &quot;
&quot;He was wrong... the respondent&#39;s complete disregard to accord the applicant any natural justice in dismissing her was shockingly disrespectful and grossly unfair.&quot;
Mr Sams said that while Foodworks was a small business, &quot;it must be said frankly that no decent employer would dismiss employees in the grossly unfair and perfunctory manner admitted in this case.&quot;
He said: &quot;This is disgraceful and extremely unfair.&quot;
Guangzhou Railway welcomes the National Day Golden Week passenger flow increases by 175 passenger trains - China News Service
