China is expected to become Australia&#39;s largest beef export market.
An animal protein analyst at Rabobank said China is expected to become Australia&#39;s largest beef export market as it faces a severe pork shortage following an outbreak of African swine fever.
Chinese consumers are switching from pork to other animal proteins after the outbreak, which caused authorities to destroy many herds, has cut China&#39;s pig population in half and nearly doubled pork prices in the past year.
China produces and consumes two-thirds of the world&#39;s pork.
Chenjun Pan, senior animal protein analyst at Rabobank China, said demand for other meats, including beef, has increased, and China, the world&#39;s largest importer of animal protein, currently accounts for 10% of the world&#39;s pork imports. 27% of the world&#39;s beef imports account for 24%.
Ms. Pan said that in the first half of this year, China&#39;s beef imports from Australia increased by 65%, and China surpassed the United States and Japan to become Australia&#39;s largest beef export market.
Yesterday, the Chinese government said it would release more pork from emergency reserves ahead of celebrating the 70th anniversary of the Chinese Communist Party&#39;s rule.
