The world&#39;s oldest barber dies at 108 after cutting hair for 96 years
In New York, USA, there is Anthony Mancinelli, the oldest barber in the world certified by Guinness World Records. At 108 years old, he has never retired and diligently cuts hair for his clients every day. However, on the 19th, Mancinelli was diagnosed with a chin injury. He passed away due to cancer complications and bid farewell to his 96-year hair-cutting life.
According to &quot;CNN&quot;, Mancinelli immigrated to the United States when he was 8 years old. Soon he was helping to clean the floor in a barber shop. When he was 12 years old, he began to pick up scissors to serve customers to relieve the financial pressure on his family.
Although Mancinelli attended elementary school at the time, he did not graduate.
Mancinelli&#39;s son Robert revealed that his father loved his job and people from all over the world also liked him. However, although his father had always been healthy, he was diagnosed with cancer in February this year. He finally died of physical factors 6 weeks before his death. He is unable to work, but this is not retirement, because he plans to come back and get his hair cut when he gets better.
Robert, 82, said he now had to find a new hairdresser after his father passed away because he had had his hair cut all his life.
The scale of buybacks by listed companies during the year exceeded 100 billion yuan, a record high - Xinhuanet
In order to stabilize the company&#39;s stock price and maintain the company&#39;s image, listed companies have begun to frequently repurchase shares in the past two years. Through targeted repurchases, collective bidding transactions, etc., they hope to convey the information that the company&#39;s value is undervalued to the market, thereby stabilizing the stock price and enhancing Investor confidence.
Oriental Fortune Choice data shows that the funds used by listed companies to repurchase shares in 2017 were 7.9 billion yuan, which surged to 51 billion yuan in 2018. Since 2019, the total amount of repurchases implemented by A-share listed companies has exceeded 100 billion yuan. , setting a new high in the amount of A-share repurchase funds in history, and far exceeding previous years.
From the perspective of the purpose of the repurchase, the company&#39;s repurchase of shares and the increase of holdings by major shareholders seem to be the same, but there are big differences in the implementation entities, sources of funds, purposes of repurchase, and the equity of the stock itself.
Xu Yang, chairman of Shanghai Maikerong Information Consulting Co., Ltd., said in an interview with a reporter from Securities Daily that the &quot;Opinions on Supporting the Repurchase of Shares by Listed Companies&quot; issued in November 2018 has a narrow scope for share repurchases. Problems in the current system such as complex decision-making procedures and incomplete inventory systems were repaired. Since the policy had previously begun to encourage listed companies to repurchase shares, the phenomenon of share repurchases increased significantly that year.
In January this year, the Shanghai Stock Exchange and the Shenzhen Stock Exchange officially released the &quot;Detailed Implementation Rules for the Repurchase of Shares by Listed Companies.&quot; The introduction of these policies has broadened the sources of funds for listed companies&#39; repurchases, appropriately simplified implementation procedures, guided and improved governance arrangements, and encouraged all types of listed companies to implement Equity incentive or employee stock ownership plan.
After the promulgation of the opinions, listed companies have more applicable situations for share repurchase, the repurchase process is simpler, and the enthusiasm for share repurchase is greater.
Repurchasing shares at a relatively low position can also help listed companies improve the efficiency of capital use, thereby increasing the level of earnings per share, improving return on net assets, and reducing the pressure on the company&#39;s profitability indicators.
Compared with the increase in holdings by major shareholders, the repurchase of shares by listed companies is of greater significance, and also reflects the listed companies&#39; willingness to proactively manage market value and abundant cash flow.
Xu Yang believes that underestimation of stock prices is the main factor in the buyback of listed companies. The company&#39;s stock price can no longer reflect the company&#39;s future development prospects. Therefore, such companies deserve investors&#39; attention, but they cannot invest blindly. They need to pay attention to such listed companies. financial reports and specific operating conditions.
Listed companies that engage in large-scale repurchases at least demonstrate the company&#39;s development confidence and financial strength.
The enthusiasm for repurchases of A-share listed companies has gradually increased, which has also normalized repurchase behavior. Data shows that nearly a thousand listed companies have implemented share repurchases this year, and leading companies in various industries have become the main force in the repurchase market.
Ping An of China recently disclosed its repurchase progress, saying that the company has repurchased a total of 57.59 million A-shares through centralized bidding transactions, accounting for 0.315% of the company&#39;s total share capital, and the total funds paid have totaled 5 billion yuan (excluding transaction fees). All repurchased shares will be used for employee stock ownership plans, including but not limited to long-term service plans that have been reviewed and approved by the company&#39;s general meeting of shareholders.
Yili has paid 5.792 billion yuan for share repurchase, and has recently adjusted the use of repurchased shares. The original plan of &quot;all repurchased shares will be used as a source of stocks for the later implementation of equity incentives&quot; has been changed to &quot;accumulated repurchases&quot;. 183 million shares will be purchased, of which 152 million shares will be used to implement equity incentive stock sources, and the remaining 30.49 million shares will be used for cancellation to reduce registered capital.&quot;
Yili Co., Ltd. said that canceling some of the repurchased shares will help further increase the level of earnings per share and effectively improve the investment return of the company&#39;s shareholders.
TCL Group released a repurchase progress announcement on September 25, which showed that TCL Group had repurchased a total of 3.59% of the company&#39;s shares at a total cost of 1.65 billion yuan.
The TCL Group Board of Directors Office told a reporter from Securities Daily that the repurchased shares will be used for employee stock ownership plans, equity incentives or for converting corporate bonds issued by listed companies that can be converted into stocks.
TCL Group adheres to its established business strategy, continuously improves its competitiveness, and achieves sustained and healthy development.
Based on the confidence in the company&#39;s future development and the protection of investors&#39; interests, combined with the performance of the company&#39;s secondary market in the past year, and comprehensive consideration of the company&#39;s operating conditions and financial status and other factors, the company plans to use its own funds, self-raised funds and Other financing methods include repurchasing company shares.
Yang Delong, chief economist of Qianhai Kaiyuan Fund, said that the operation of stock repurchases by listed companies can, on the one hand, reduce the number of shares circulating in the market and increase the earnings per share of listed companies, which is an important benefit to the stock price in the secondary market; In addition, listed companies are willing to take the initiative to spend real money to repurchase shares from the stock market and cancel them, which has greatly boosted market confidence.
Buybacks of domestic listed companies have gradually increased in recent years, especially for blue chip stocks. Boosting investor confidence through share buybacks is a very good way and a practice worthy of recognition and encouragement.
