Research: The U.S. National Healthy Eating Index has increased slightly but remains challenging - China News Service
China News Service, September 27. According to the American Overseas Chinese News Network, a recent study in the United States showed that the U.S. government’s healthy eating index has increased moderately over the past 16 years, from 56 to 58.
But with a perfect score of 100, that&#39;s not cause for celebration.
Americans still face &quot;significant challenges&quot; in their diet.
One of the study&#39;s authors, Dr. Fangfang Zhang, a nutrition researcher at Tufts University in Massachusetts, said Americans still eat too much food that may cause heart disease, diabetes, obesity and other diseases, which are the most common diseases in the United States. The disease you suffer from.
This study was published in the Journal of the American Medical Association on the 24th.
The study is based on U.S. government health surveys of 44,000 adults from 1999 to 2016.
&quot;Despite considerable improvements, significant dietary challenges remain,&quot; the authors wrote.
It is reported that these challenges include getting American people to reduce their intake of snacks, hot dogs, fatty beef, butter and other foods containing saturated fat.
The study found that people&#39;s daily dietary intake of these unhealthy fats increased from 11.5% to 12%, exceeding the recommended intake limit of 10%.
The biggest improvement in the American national diet is that sugar intake has dropped from 16% to about 14%, but the intake is still too high.
Officials believe that the intake of added sugars in the daily diet should be less than 10%.
As for the reason for the decrease in sugar intake, researchers believe that it is related to the decrease in people drinking sweetened sodas, but Zhang Fangfang emphasized that sugar is often added to even less sweet foods, such as yogurt and ketchup.
U.S. adults&#39; consumption of fruits, nuts, oats, and other whole grain foods increased slightly.
However, data from 2016 shows that these foods still account for less than 5% of the daily diet.
Although people are eating slightly less salt and drinking less fruit juice, which results in lower-quality carbohydrate intake, Zhang Fangfang said they still account for up to 42% of daily calories, many of which come from highly processed white bread. and other refined grains.
The study is based on biennial personal health surveys, which ask adults to recall what they ate in the past 24 hours.
These health surveys have asked this question twice every few days since 2003.
The dietary guidelines for Americans issued by the government recommend that people adopt &quot;healthy eating patterns&quot; to reduce the possibility of chronic diseases.
The guidelines point out that people should eat more nutrient-dense foods, such as vegetables, fruits, whole grains, low-fat dairy products, as well as seafood, lean meats, poultry, eggs, and seeds that can provide protein.
During the study period, the number of Americans with diabetes nearly doubled to more than 7 percent, and obesity rates also increased over the years—about 70 percent of American adults are now overweight or obese.
Additionally, heart disease remains the leading cause of death in the United States.
