The record for the deepest railway tunnel shaft in China has been broken
China News Service, Baoshan, September 27 (Zhang Weiming, Xu Weiguo, Zhou Jingbo) After more than 1,200 days of day and night construction, the No. 1 shaft of the Gaoligongshan Tunnel of the Dali-Rui-Li Railway under construction was completed on the 27th, and the shaft depth reached the ground At 762.59 meters below, it breaks the record for the deepest railway tunnel shaft in China, and this record was set despite a large amount of water inflow.
The 34.5-kilometer-long Gaoligongshan Tunnel of the Dali-Ruili Railway is located in Yunnan. The tunnel crosses the Gaoligongshan Mountains from the west bank of the Nu River and is the longest double-track single-hole tunnel in Asia.
This tunnel crosses 19 fault zones with a maximum burial depth of 1,155 meters. Because it covers almost all adverse geology and major risks that may be encountered in tunnel construction, the Gaoligong Mountain Tunnel is called the &quot;Geological Museum&quot; of tunnel construction.
The shaft is the most important auxiliary tunnel of the Gaoligongshan Tunnel. It shoulders the important task of increasing the working surface to achieve &quot;long tunnel tunneling&quot; and ventilation for later railway operations.
The No. 1 shaft was successfully excavated to the bottom, marking the official entry of the Gaoligong Mountain Tunnel into horizontal tunnel construction. After the bottom shaft yard is excavated and equipment is replaced, four more working surfaces can be added underground to speed up the tunnel&#39;s main tunnel excavation.
&quot;The shafts are all in the granite formation. Because there are many fissures in the granite formation, the water cannot be stopped and flows from top to bottom. Basically, the water pressure will be as deep as the well. &quot;
Si Jingzhao, chief engineer of the Dali-Ruili Railway Project Department of China Railway Tunnel Bureau, told reporters that during the construction of the shaft, dangers such as mud and water surges and collapses occurred many times. The builder invited experts to check the pulse on site and discussed solutions more than 20 times.
&quot;When the water inflow in the shaft reaches its maximum, it reaches more than 300 cubic meters per hour. The water pressure at the bottom of the well more than 700 meters deep is equivalent to the seabed 700 meters deep. &quot;
Si Jingzhao said, &quot;If the water is not pumped and drained in time, the well will flood 10 meters in one hour. We spend almost 85% of the time controlling the water and 15% of the time digging. &quot;
In order to overcome geological problems such as the development of longitudinal joints in the surrounding rocks of Shaft No. 1, sudden mud and water intrusion, and water-rich granite, the tunnel construction adopts systematic water control measures that combine &quot;exploration, injection, and excavation&quot; to reduce construction risks.
After many improvements, the construction of No. 1 Shaft has formed a mechanized assembly line such as excavation system, ballast removal system, suspension system, and winch lifting system, realizing full-process mechanized operations such as drilling, blasting, ballast removal, formwork installation, and concrete pouring. , speeding up the construction progress.
Finally, after more than 1,200 days and nights of construction, the shaft was successfully excavated to a depth of 762.59 meters.
The Dali-Ruili Railway, with a total length of 330 kilometers, is an important part of the China-Myanmar international corridor and an important transportation infrastructure for the implementation of the &quot;Belt and Road&quot; construction.
After it is completed and opened to traffic, the driving time from Dali to Ruili will be shortened from the current 6 hours to 2 hours. This will greatly improve the transportation pattern in western Yunnan and play a role in promoting economic and trade cooperation and friendly personnel exchanges between China and South and Southeast Asian countries. enhancement.
