Prior to this, Chinese high school graduates who wanted to apply to German universities needed to study for one semester (211,985 universities) or three semesters (general undergraduate) in domestic undergraduates and pass the APS review or TestAS exam.
The release of the new regulations may save at least half a year for Chinese students who are willing to study in Germany.
It is reported that the new regulations will take effect in the second half of 2019.
Applicants need to meet the following requirements: complete 12 years of formal compulsory education and obtain a high school diploma; take the college entrance examination and college entrance examination, and the college entrance examination score reaches 70% or above of the total score (if the total score is 750 points, the score must be 525 or above), and among them Requirements include two language scores and one math or natural science score.
In addition, specific majors have different requirements for college entrance examination scores.
For example, to apply for medicine, stomatology, veterinary medicine, pharmacy and other majors, the college entrance examination score must reach 80% of the full score, and the college entrance examination subjects must include at least two of mathematics, physics, chemistry, biology, or take a science comprehensive; apply For law majors, the college entrance examination score must reach 80% of the full score, and the college entrance examination subjects must include at least two of foreign languages, history, geography, or take a liberal arts comprehensive.
According to incomplete statistics, many countries, including Germany, the United Kingdom, Canada, Australia, etc., have recognized China’s college entrance examination results.
Taking the UK as an example, universities such as the University of Cambridge, the University of Birmingham, and the University of Leicester all accept applications from Chinese students based on their college entrance examination scores.
