According to Australia.com, after a marathon debate and weeks of protests, on September 26, local time, New South Wales passed a bill legalizing abortion.
It is reported that the bill has triggered political debate in the past eight weeks. Since independent MP Greenwich announced the introduction of the bill, serious divisions have emerged within the Australian Liberal Party.
According to reports, after nearly 40 hours of discussion, the Australia and New Zealand Senate passed the abortion legalization bill by a vote of 26 to 14 on the evening of the 25th, making it the third longest bill to be considered by the New South Wales Senate.
On the morning of the 26th, the New State House of Representatives held a final vote, making abortion legal in New South Wales.
The bill allows women to terminate pregnancies as early as 22 weeks, and also allows women to have abortions later in pregnancy if two doctors agree.
The Senate passed an amendment on the evening of the 25th that allows doctors to seek advice from the multidisciplinary panel of the hospital advisory committee before performing an abortion on a woman after 22 weeks of pregnancy.
Additionally, the Senate-passed amendment would require doctors to provide appropriate care for babies who survive a pregnancy termination.
Previously, NSW Premier Gladys Berejiklian had faced public criticism from conservatives over the bill. Gladys Berejiklian had intervened multiple times to get more debate time for the bill, but she did not attend the final vote.
Berejiklian defended her absentee vote: &quot;I need to spend my time running the whole state.&quot;
It is reported that Australian Liberal Party MP Davis was once the strongest opponent of the abortion bill. He once threatened to withdraw from the New South Wales government because of the bill, saying that the bill triggered a &quot;government crisis.&quot;
But then Davis backed down.
Davis said: &quot;The content of the amendment to the abortion legalization bill submitted to the House of Representatives on the morning of the 26th actually provides more protections for women and doctors. &quot;
Meanwhile, NSW Nationals leader Barilaro said he was proud to be part of the government that decriminalized abortion.
&quot;What we achieved last night is historic for NSW, it decriminalizes abortion, decriminalizes it and treats women who have abortions as criminals.&quot;
