The Hong Kong government launches a free special training program to help employees who have been recently affected by the economy tide over the difficulties
The Hong Kong SAR government announced on the 27th that it has launched a free special training program for employees who have been affected by the recent economic situation. Eligible trainees will receive a monthly training subsidy of up to HK$4,000 after completing the course.
Many boutiques in Harbor City, Tsim Sha Tsui, Hong Kong, had very few customers.
Affected by the recent social strife in Hong Kong, the number of tourists visiting Hong Kong has dropped significantly recently. In addition to the tourism industry, the hotel, catering, retail and other industries have also been affected.
Law Chi-kwong, Secretary for Labor and Welfare of the Hong Kong SAR Government, and Edward Yau, Secretary for Commerce and Economic Development, met with the media on entrusting the Employees Retraining Board to implement special training programs and measures to support the tourism industry.
Law Chi-kwong described that the challenges facing Hong Kong&#39;s economy are imminent and we should not wait until the situation calms down before starting work.
Therefore, the Hong Kong SAR government launched this free training program called &quot;Special? Love Added Value&quot;.
According to reports, people who have lost their jobs or been asked to take unpaid leave by their employers since June 1 will have the opportunity to participate in the plan as long as they meet the relevant requirements.
Luo Zhiguang introduced that the scope of relevant courses is very wide, the most important part of which is &quot;vocational skills&quot; training, covering 19 industries, including tourism, retail and catering industries, etc. There will also be some new &quot;innovative technology&quot; courses, as well as cross-border A “general skills” course for the industry.
Chairman of the Employees Retraining Board Yu Pengchun said that all courses are free of charge and the program is expected to support about 10,000 people in need.
Students participating in the program will receive a special subsidy as long as they complete each full-time or part-time course with an attendance rate of 80%. The maximum monthly subsidy for each student is HK$4,000.
According to reports, the training courses last for 2 to 3 months and are provided by about 50 training institutions. Citizens can register from October 3 to March 31 next year, and each person can register for up to 4 courses.
In addition, the Hong Kong SAR government also announced a series of measures to support the tourism industry to help the industry tide over the difficulties.
These measures include relaxing funding for the Tourism Industry Council, subsidizing 6,000 tour guides to renew their licenses and enrolling in courses, and waiving annual fees for travel agents.
Is exercise tiring for both the body and the brain?
According to the Russian Sputnik Network, a study conducted on athletes showed that the brain also shows signs of fatigue after high-intensity exercise.
The study, led by Matthias Pessiglione, a specialist at the Pitiers-Salpetrier Hospital in France, shows that there is an obscure link between mental and physical work: both require recognition of activities. Knowledge control.
&quot;You need to control the voluntary process of forcing yourself to stop when there is pain in your muscles and joints,&quot; Pessiglione explains.
The study was initiated by the French National Institute of Physical Education and Sport (INSEP).
Experts from the school are responsible for guiding athletes in preparing for the Olympic Games.
Some athletes have begun to suffer from overtraining syndrome, which is an uncontrollable feeling of fatigue after high-load exercise, the body is unable to recover, and performance declines.
INSEP poses a question: Could this condition be partly caused by neurological fatigue, the kind caused by excessive mental exertion?
The research was published in the journal Current Biology.
