The central bank launches a 30 billion yuan reverse repurchase operation
Xinhua News Agency, Beijing, September 27 (Reporters Zhang Qianqian and Wu Yu) The People&#39;s Bank of China launched a 30 billion yuan reverse repurchase operation through interest rate bidding on the 27th.
Since 40 billion yuan of reverse repurchase expired that day, the People&#39;s Bank of China&#39;s reverse repurchase operation achieved a net withdrawal of 10 billion yuan.
The central bank issued an announcement stating that it would launch a 30 billion yuan reverse repurchase operation that day, with a period of 14 days and a winning interest rate of 2.7%.
This is the seventh consecutive working day that the central bank has carried out 14-day reverse repurchase operations.
The Shanghai Interbank Offered Rate (Shibor) released on the 27th showed that the overnight interest rate was 1.313%, down 32.4 basis points from the previous trading day; the 7-day interest rate was 2.59%, up 1.3 basis points from the previous trading day; 14 The daily interest rate was 2.95%, 1.7 basis points lower than the previous trading day; the one-year interest rate was 3.048%, the same as the previous trading day.
Make Chinese citizens feel more at ease when &quot;going global&quot; - Interview with Cui Aimin, Director of the Consular Department of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs
No matter where you go, the motherland is behind you.
On the 25th, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs’ first public welfare short film on consular protection was launched online. The sentence at the end of the short film resonated with the majority of netizens.
Cui Aimin, director of the Consular Department of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, said in an interview with Xinhua News Agency that the short film aims to further let the public feel the sentiment and warmth of &quot;diplomacy for the people&quot; and let Chinese citizens feel that no matter where they are in the world, Chinese diplomats We will all lend a helping hand to them, giving them help, strength and hope.
There is no small matter in overseas safety, and every branch and leaf is always about love.
Cui Aimin said that over the past 70 years, the number of Chinese citizens &quot;going abroad&quot; has increased dramatically, from &quot;less than one million per year&quot; before the reform and opening up to more than 100 million people per year today; at the same time, the safety of Chinese citizens traveling overseas has been more secure. , the targets of consular protection and assistance have also expanded from overseas Chinese to various groups such as overseas Chinese, tourists, international students, and migrant workers.
According to statistics, since the 18th National Congress of the Communist Party of China, we have organized and implemented more than 10 major operations to evacuate or transfer overseas Chinese citizens, safely evacuating more than 40,000 Chinese citizens from dangerous and unstable areas.
It has accepted and coordinated the handling of approximately 500,000 cases of various types of requests for help, involving nearly 1 million Chinese citizens.
In times of danger, the motherland can take you home; wanting to take a &quot;just-go trip&quot; is no longer a dream now.
According to Cui Aimin, as of the end of August this year, China has concluded mutual visa exemption agreements with 14 countries covering ordinary passport holders.
In addition, more and more countries are unilaterally granting entry conveniences such as visa exemption or visa on arrival to Chinese citizens.
42 countries and regions, including Thailand and Egypt, unilaterally grant visa-on-arrival to Chinese citizens holding ordinary passports, and 15 other countries and regions, including Indonesia, unilaterally allow visa-free entry to Chinese citizens holding ordinary passports.
In addition to arrangements such as visa exemption and visa on arrival, it is becoming more and more convenient for Chinese citizens to apply for visas and the procedures are becoming more and more simplified.
As of the end of August, China had reached agreements or arrangements with 41 countries to simplify visa procedures.
These include agreements with the United States, Canada, Israel, and Argentina to issue 10-year multiple-entry visas to each other&#39;s tourism and business personnel, and agreements with the United Kingdom to issue two-year multiple-entry visas to each other&#39;s tourism, business, and family visits.
The United Kingdom and Belgium jointly launched a &quot;one-stop visa&quot; service, and France, Italy and Singapore shortened the visa processing time to 48 hours, 36 hours and 24 hours respectively.
For business people who often go abroad, the APEC business travel card with multiple entries and convenient customs clearance is a good choice.
According to Cui Aimin, holding this travel card is equivalent to obtaining a five-year multiple visa from 16 economies around the Asia-Pacific, which is of great significance to business personnel, especially private enterprise personnel, in &quot;going global.&quot;
Currently, China ranks first among APEC economies in terms of valid card holders.
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs will actively negotiate bilateral visa reciprocity agreements, promote more countries to adopt visa facilitation measures for Chinese citizens, transform the results of diplomatic work into more people-benefiting and convenient measures, and continuously increase the &#39;gold content&#39; of Chinese passports.
