Taiwanese scholars suggest: &quot;In uncertain times&quot; Taiwanese businessmen need to follow the mainland in developing mainstream industries
The &quot;2019 Taiwanese Businessmen Innovative Operation Model Forum&quot; was held in Taipei for two consecutive days on the 26th and 27th.
The event invited a number of Taiwanese business representatives and scholars to share their experiences on corporate transformation, innovation, succession and market development.
The forum was hosted by the Taipei Institute of Management and Management, and co-organized by organizations such as Qunyi Jinding Securities and the Association of Outstanding Mainland and Taiwanese Businessmen.
The two-day meeting was divided into multiple seminars on transformation and upgrading models, business strategies, etc., with more than 100 people in attendance.
Chen Mingzhang, president of the Taipei Institute of Management, said that with the ongoing trade friction between China (Mainland China) and the United States, Taiwanese businessmen are facing an &quot;era of uncertainty.&quot;
He believes that Taiwanese businessmen need to keep pace with the times and keep up with the development of mainstream industries in the mainland, with special attention to innovative products related to technology, culture, tourism, and health.
&quot;In the past, Taiwanese businessmen valued quality, results and delivery. &quot;
Chen Mingzhang believes that the above-mentioned conditions are no longer enough for Taiwanese businessmen at present.
He pointed out that Taiwan-funded enterprises must combine speed and service, speed up the supply chain, and pay attention to extended services and lifestyle product services.
In addition, &quot;service value-added&quot; is also a new area that Taiwanese businessmen can vigorously develop.
During the speech session on behalf of Taiwanese businessmen, Xu Wentang, chairman of Yayi Electronics Co., Ltd., a Taiwanese businessman from Guangdong, said that Yayi Electronics had operational difficulties due to a sudden drop in orders, and the group began to improve its operating conditions from multiple aspects such as structural adjustment and asset activation.
It took three years to close the traditional electrical appliance business, transform automotive electronic equipment, and enter the smart home appliance industry before the company achieved revenue.
Bai Hongzhang, general manager of Helios (Zhuhai) Electronics Co., Ltd., suggested that if it is difficult to develop new customers, it is better to focus on original customers and provide &quot;one-stop&quot; services.
Customers switch suppliers due to six factors: poor service, high prices, low quality, slow delivery, few varieties, and integrity issues. As long as these six points are solved, as well as timely transformation of production lines and expansion of product categories, enterprises will automatically become Suppliers that are not replaceable by customers.
