Soliciting opinions on new regulations: Qualifications are required for social capital to obtain rural land management rights
Qualifications are required for social capital to obtain rural land management rights
The &quot;Measures for the Administration of the Transfer of Rural Land Management Rights&quot; is publicly soliciting opinions and intends to supervise the transfer of social capital such as industrial and commercial enterprises to obtain land management rights.
Yesterday, the website of the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Affairs issued a notice for public comment on the &quot;Measures for the Management of the Transfer of Rural Land Management Rights (Revised Draft for Comments)&quot; (hereinafter referred to as the &quot;Draft&quot;), which added requirements for the transfer of land acquired by social capital such as industrial and commercial enterprises. Supervision and risk prevention of operating rights.
The &quot;Draft for Opinions&quot; will be open to the public for comments from now on.
The Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Affairs stated that in order to implement the newly revised &quot;Rural Land Contract Law&quot;, further consolidate and improve the basic rural management system, deepen the reform of the rural land system, and implement the &quot;separation of three powers&quot; system, the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Affairs has revised the &quot;Rural Land Contract Law&quot; The &quot;Measures for the Management of Transfer of Operation Rights&quot; were revised and the &quot;Draft of Opinions&quot; was formed.
A reporter from the Beijing Youth Daily learned that the &quot;Draft of Opinions&quot; released for the first time has many important revisions.
The newly revised &quot;Rural Land Contract Law&quot; clarifies the scope of land transfer, implements the concept of &quot;separation of three rights&quot;, and sets up special sections for &quot;Land Contract Management Rights&quot; and &quot;Land Management Rights&quot; respectively, and regulates the transfer and mutual transfer of land contract management rights. A clear distinction is made between the exchange and the transfer of land management rights (leasing, subcontracting, equity participation or other methods).
In this &quot;Opinion Draft&quot;, in order to implement the concept of &quot;separation of three rights&quot;, effectively respond to the gist of the amendment to the &quot;Rural Land Contract Law&quot;, and take into account the transfer of land management rights and the exchange and transfer of land contract management rights, the parties and procedures are , supervision and other aspects. This revised draft defines the scope of transfer, focusing on the transfer of land management rights. The transfer methods include leasing, shareholding, etc., and the name of the regulation is changed from &quot;Measures for the Administration of Transfer of Rural Land Contract Management Rights&quot; It is the &quot;Measures for the Administration of Transfer of Rural Land Management Rights&quot;.
Separate management measures will be issued to regulate the transfer and exchange of land contract management rights.
The &quot;Opinion Draft&quot; points out that in the context of &quot;separation of three rights&quot;, farmers only have land management rights for a certain period of time.
Theoretically speaking, even if bankruptcy liquidation occurs, farmers only have the risk of losing their management rights for a certain period of time. Therefore, it is no longer necessary to provide that the contracted land should be returned to the original contracting household, and it also conflicts with the Bankruptcy Law.
In order to prevent farmers from the risk of losing their land, methods such as preferred shares, rent first and shares later, and buyback have emerged in practice.
Considering that preferred shares have relatively mature theoretical discussions in corporate law, it is recommended that they be used as an advocacy provision to prevent the risk of losing land when investing in shares.
